<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the National Association for Youth Justice (NAYJ) (JRR 0003)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The National Association for Youth Justice (NAYJ) welcomes the opportunity to give evidence to the Joint Committee on Human Rights on the above.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NAYJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is the only membership </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">organisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is exclusively concerned with the rights of and just</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ice for children an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d young people in trouble</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with the law. NAYJ was formed in 1995 following the amalg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">amation of two existing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the Association for Youth Justice and the National</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Intermediate Treatment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Federation and in 2010 became a registere</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d charity. NAYJ seek</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s to promote the welfare of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children and young people in the Youth Justice system in England b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y conducting research;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> publishing newsletters and briefing papers on youth justice policy and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> practice; organizing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">training events and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">conferences; responding to government cons</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ultations/lobbying and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> campaigning on issues that directly affect the needs and rights of children in trouble. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In paragraphs 20 – 105 we address the four specific areas the Committee requests evidence on, namely </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">standing and third party interventions, costs, procedural as opposed to substantive defects in decisions and the Public Sector Equality Duty. However in paragraphs 4 – 19 we wish to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">first put forward our general concerns of the devastating effects these re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">forms would have on access to justice and human rights, made in reference to specific comments of the MOJ in this consultation paper and the Lord Chancellor.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are concerned that the proposal’s in the Ministry of Justice’s (MOJ) consultation paper fail t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o properly address the human rights of children. In particular we are concerned that the proposals fail to consider children as a group of people distinct from adults. We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ask the Committee to accept </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that if these proposals apply to children, they are incom</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">patible with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">United Nations Convention on the Rights of the Child 1989</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In particular Article 12 states: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Parties shall assure to the child who is capable of forming his or her own views the right to </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">express those views freely in all matters affectin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">g the child, the views of the child being </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">given due weight in accordance with the age and maturity of the child.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">For this purpose the child shall in particular be provided the opportunity to be heard in any judicial and administrative proceedings </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">affecting the child, either directly, or through a representative or appropriate body, in a manner consistent with the procedural rules of national law.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We also refer the Committee to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Baroness Hale at paragraph 23 of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">ZH (Tanzania) (FC) (Apellant) V</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Secretary of State for the Home Department [2011] UKSC 4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">states,  'This is a binding obligation </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in international law, and the spirit, if not the precise language, has also been translated into our </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">national law.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Judicial review upholds the rule of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">law and remains the ess</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ential mechanism by which the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> individual can hold the State to account. This applies to children </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and young people as well, if </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not more so, than adults. Very few people can afford to bring these appli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cations if they are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> required to be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ar their own</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> legal costs. In the case of children,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> they are dependent on their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cases being brought by their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> parents/guardians’ or by cha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rities and/or non government bodies (NGOs) on their behalf.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Often judicial review cases are funded by legal aid. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We note with concern the comments made by the Lord Chancellor as reported by the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Daily Mail on 6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> September 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">'Of course, the judicial review system is an important way to right wrongs, but it is not a      promotional tool for countless Left-wing ca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">mpaigners. So that is why we are publishing our       proposals for change. We will protect the parts of judicial review that are essential to justice,     but stop the abuse.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> Britain cannot afford to allow a culture of Left-wing-dominated, single-issu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">e activism to hold </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> back our country from investing in infrastructure and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> new sources of energy and from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">bringing</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> down the cost of our welfare state.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">We need to make decisions quicker and respond to issues more quickly in what is a true</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> global race.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The Left does not understand this, and believes that our society can do everything for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">  e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">veryone,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">nd that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">those who work hard to get on in life should pick up the tab.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">They want more money for public services, but at the same time to be able to halt </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">the investments which can deliver the wealth that pays for those services.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">n proposing these changes, I will no doubt be accused of killing justice and destroying Magna</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Carta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">. Although as the great old lady of British law is approaching her 800th birthd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ay, and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">judicial review system is barely 40, I’m not sure that argument stacks up. But in proposing  these changes, I know we will be doing the right thing for Britain.' </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst the Lord Chancellor’s comments may have been in some part specific to ju</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dicial reviews brought on environmental/plann</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing interests the NAYJ has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> concern that he expresses his  views in political terms with a heavy regard towards economical value for money. Judicial review is not political and certainly not a left-win</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g mechanism. It is a means of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">holding those who make and uphold the law to account</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and ensure the correct and just decisions are made, not just speedy ones</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. We sincerely hope that the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Lord Chancellor regrets these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> comments in light of our submissions in o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ur response on behalf of the need for access to justice  on behalf of Britain’s children.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We remind the Committee that the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> MOJ’s response to the consultation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> “Transforming Legal Aid” </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has upheld the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> proposal to limit access to legal aid to individuals, inc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">luding children, for prison law issues an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to those individu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">als, again including children, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">who fail to meet the strict criteria under the “residency test”. The further proposals will undoubtedly remove for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">these</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> groups the current access they hav</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e to the A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dministrative Court and the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ability to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">challenge the State and public bodies i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n a yet unknown landscape of th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e effects</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of these drastic yet</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> decided cuts.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee may be faced with the MOJ attempting to justify these proposals by asserting </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">they are</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> financially necessary and in line with other austerity cuts. However, the </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reforms arising from the previous consultation, </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">'Judicial Review: proposals for reform',</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have again not yet been quantified. Indeed, some of these changes only came into effect on 1</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> July 2013. The transfer of immigration and asylum judicial review cases from the Administrative Court to the Upper Tribunal will take place from 1 November 2013. The</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> outcome of the</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">'Transforming Legal Aid: The next steps” </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">consultation is not yet known. </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In short, </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NAYJ is concerned and asks the Committee to consider that </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the MOJ is acting in a premature, uninformed manner as regards what financial benefit these proposals could achieve and at what cost to justice given the yet to be assessed effects on the </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rule of law the changes already implicat</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed will have.</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We refer the Committee to</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Lord Dyson’s comments in </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">R (on the application of Cart) v The Upper Tribunal [2010] EWCA </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Civ</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> 859, </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">para</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> 122:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“There is no principle more basic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">to our system of law than the mai</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ntenance of the rule of law itself and the constitutional protection afforded by judicial review”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NAYJ therefore wish to express our firm opposition to these proposals on the basis that they have not been shown to be financially necessary and are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">constitutionally dangerous, especially to children.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NAYJ does not accept that “too many unmeritorious judicial review applications are being issued” </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as stated in the MOJ’</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s c</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">onsultation paper and refer the Committee</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to the Bingham Centre for the Rule </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Law’s response to the </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">previous J</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">udicial Review consultation. We ask the Committee to consider that the MOJ </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has failed to reco</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gnise the fact that an </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">application for judicial review that is withdrawn or settled without the need for a full and final hearin</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g does not mean the application lacks merit. Many such app</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lications end this way </span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">because the public body defending the claim recognises that the application has ut</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">most merit</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and acknowledges that they have no real prospect of successfully defending the case.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In any event, any case that does lack all merit would now be brought to a swift end given the new powers of judges to prevent the case progressing to an oral renewal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">where permission is refused by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">categorising</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it as “totally without merit”. Such cases are likely to be few and far between and robustly case managed to ensure a short case life by the judiciary. The “end of case” data that all legal aid providers are oblig</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed to complete would continue to give a clear picture of just how many publicly funded cases fail. This data has not been published but is and would remain available should the MOJ wish to disclose and engage in an informed dialogue regarding it.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ask the Committee to request this data and insist on such a dialogue regarding it with the MOJ.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NAYJ does not accept, and asks the Committee to also consider that “Judicial review is pursued as a campaign strategy by groups to generate publicity or as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a delaying tactic”, as also stated by the MOJ in this consultation paper. We refer the Committee to the recent successful application for judicial review, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">R on the application of HC (a child, by his litigation friend, CC) and the Secretary of State for th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">e Home Department and The Commissioner of the Police of the Metropolis [2013] EWHC 982 (Admin).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This judicial review was initially brought by the charitable organization, Just for Kids Law. The application was supported by the Coram Children’s Law Centre a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd The Howard League for Penal Reform and successfully challenged the provisions of the treatment of 17 year olds in police custody. The charitable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> involved in this case were acting in the interests of a specific individual’s family but with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a view to the wider implications this would have for all 17 year olds in police custody. It certainly cannot be argued that the case was brought on the basis of generating publicity for these groups. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It certainly can be argued that this addressed the Artic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">le 5 rights of children in police detention.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We fu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rther refer the Committee </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to the case </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">of R (on the application of The Howa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">rd League for Penal Reform) v </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Secretary of State for the Home Department (interested party) [2002] EWHC 2497</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> (Admin)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This case successfully argued that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Children</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Act 1989</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> did apply to children in Youth Offender Institutions or other Prison Service establishments subject to the necessary requirements of imprisonment. It also resulted in a declaration that the statement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Prison Service Order 4950: Regimes for Prisoners under 18 years old</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“The Children Act 1989 does not apply to under 18 year olds in prison establishments”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is wrong in law. This is a clear example of a judicial review claim brought by a non-gove</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rnmental agency which dealt with matters of wide public interest. Indeed, at paragraph 2, Mr Justice </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Munby</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> states:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The proceedings have been brought by The Howard League for Penal Reform whose history and credentials need no introduction. It undoubtedly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">is, as it claims to be, the leading non-governmental organisation in this country concerned with penal issues and policy. Here I need only to note that in the last decade or so it has had a particular focus on children and young people in the criminal just</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ice system.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Certainly, if some charities, NGOs and campaigning groups were not able to bring judicial review proceedings there is a great risk that some government action will be impossible to challenge. The research done by the Public Law Project and th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e University of Essex, funded by the Nuffield Foundation concluded that judicial review proceedings brought by NGOs in respect of matters of wider public interest are few and far between. It is unclear what evidence the MOJ relies upon to make this asserti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In any event, whatever the motive of an NGO or charity in bringing judicial review proceedings, and whether political, left, middle or right wing, the court’s role does not change. The court is there to assess the legality of the decision of the defen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dant public body and this is unaffected by who the claimant is.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are already numerous procedural requirements to prevent judicial review causing delay to properly made decisions. The fact that a case can only be brought within 3 months, and withou</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t undue delay, with a tight pre-action timetable and court timetable in place on issue, is sufficient to balance the need to provide a means of challenging executive decision and the need to prevent unnecessary delay to public projects.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The MOJ states that “Public confidence in, and the credibility of, the legal aid system is being undermined”. There is no evidence to suggest that this is the case and certainly no evidence to support any argument that, if it is, this is because of legal a</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">id being granted for judicial review proceedings. It therefore follows that there is no evidence to suggest that if these current proposals were to go through, the public would feel gratified. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In contrast, there is evidence to show there is public suppor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t for legal aid. The recent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ComRes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> poll commissioned by the Bar Council concluded that 68% of the public believe that legal aid is a price worth paying for living in a fair society and 75% of the public say that the poorest members of society will be most </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">affected if the Government makes cuts to legal aid.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The MOJ states that “Proper executive decision making and action i</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s being hindered”. T</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he purpose of judicial review applications is to ensure that executive decisions and those of public bodies are made</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> rationally, lawfully and follow proper procedure. This comment seems to therefore suggest that the government do not understand the purpose of judicial review and see it as an “annoyance”. If the executive and public bodies make their decisions rationally</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, lawfully and follow proper procedure there would be no need for judicial review applications. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Impact Assessment MOJ 212 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">states that 'it is not a good use of public resources to fund one part of the state to challenge another and [the Government] wi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">shes to limit the circumstances under which this may take place.’ Again, this demonstrates a fundamental misunderstanding of the function of judicial review, where the constitutional purpose is for one part of the State, the judiciary, to scrutinise the ac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tions of another, the executive.  The judiciary fulfil this function not on behalf of the state but on behalf of citizens who consider that relevant authorities have acted outside of their legal powers or interpreted their powers unreasonably.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As Lord </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Neuberger has stated, to deny someone with a claim for judicial review the chance to pursue it ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is a rank denial of justice and a blot on the rule of law’.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We refer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the Committee to the response of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government’s own Treasury counsel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the previous consultation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘...judicial review provides a prompt and efficient remedy for many persons affected by government action in large numbers of cases, often of critical importance to them, which are conceded by public bodies at an early s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">tage, and at little cost either to the public body or the legal aid fund. By ensuring that officials are accountable to the law, judicial review provides a powerful corrective to poor decision making, the importance of which goes well beyond the relatively</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> small number of cases which get near a court. We consider that the proposals in the Consultation Paper will undermine the accountability of public bodies to the detriment of society as a whole and the vulnerable in particular’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">     </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The NAYJ fully agrees with this view and believes it encapsulates the negative impact this will </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">      have on access to justice and erosion of human rights.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-indent:28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Standing and third party interventions</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MOJ has raised concerns that there is a problem with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cases being brought where the claimant has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">little or no direct interest in the matter. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NAYJ sees no issue with such claimants bringing judicial review proceedings and is satisfied that the current “sufficient interest” test applied by the court should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> prevail. The test on standing, pursuant to s31(3) Senior Courts Act 1981 is clearly defined:  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘No application for judicial review shall be made unless the leave of the High Court has been obtained in accordance with rules of court; and the court shall n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ot grant leave to make such an application unless it considers that the applicant has a sufficient interest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">in the matter to which the application relates.’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NAYJ sees no need to restrict the court’s interpretation of this and disagree that this is set</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as a “low hur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dle”. The NAYJ refers to the Committee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to the research completed by the UK Constitutional Law Group October 2013. This research considered a sample of cases brought resulting in a final hearing. 77% of cases were brought by individuals, 15% b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y corporations/legal persons, 5% by local authorities and just 3% by a variety of interest groups and charities. Yet it is this group that the MOJ specifically targets as a cost saver. Over half of all cases brought by all claimants were against central go</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vernment, with the most challenged departments being the Secretary of State for the Home Department and the Secretary of State for Justice. These two departments accounted for 53% of all challenges to government departments.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The MOJ’s own statistics, as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">outlined in this consultation paper, do not support their assertion that judicial review cases brought by charities and NGOs, are problematic both in terms of any financial burden on the legal aid budget and such cases lacking merit. In 2012 12,400 judicia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l review cases were brought and only 0.4% were brought by such </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In this paper the MOJ acknowledges that cases brought by these groups “tended to be relatively more successful compared to other judicial review cases”. We are therefore concerne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d that the government wishes to limit these groups access to judicial review when there clearly is a need to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> hold the government to account and ensure that human rights are protected. We again refer the Committee </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to Mr Justice </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Munby’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> comments in respect o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f the Howard League for Penal Reform as stated in paragraph 12 above.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We ask the Committee to accept that the range of public authorities’ responsibilities to children is significantly wider (and more complex) than those to most adults. The need to protec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t their human rights is especially important.  At the same time, many of the children potentially adversely affect by public authorities failing to discharge their responsibilities in a reasonable manner, will include some of the most vulnerable people in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">society. The case of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">R (on the application of the Howard League for Penal Reform v Secretary of State for the Home Department and Department of Health (interested party) [2012] EWHC 2497 (Admin)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, discussed at paragraph 12, is a clear example of how childre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n were being adversely affected by public authorities failing to discharge their duties, a failure that was addressed in this judicial review case.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Children are ill placed to be able to identify where they have been ill served by public authorities. Justi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ce for them is therefore more likely to be dependent on charities and interest groups to bring claims for judicial review on their behalf of any irrational or unlawful behavior and decisions by public auth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">orities. We again refer the Committee </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to the case o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">R on the application of HC (a child, by his litigation friend, CC) and the Secretary of State for the Home Department and The Commissioner of the Police of the Metropolis [2013] EWHC 982 (Admin)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> discussed at paragraph 11 above. Such judicial review cases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> benefit the rights of children generally.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We also refer the Committee to the case </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">of Children’s Rights Alliance for England v the Secretary of State for Justice [2012] EWHC 8 (Admin)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This case concerned the Children’s Right Alliance for England </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">challenging the decision of the Secretary of State for Justice refusing to disclose the names of children subjected to unlawful restraint techniques at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">centres</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> run by the interested parties, an issue affecting their Article 3 rights. This was an access to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">justice issue brought to enable children to make their own claims. It is accepted that the Administrative Court did find standing to be in issue here but in terms of the “victim” test as defined in s7 Human Rights Act 1998. Sufficiency of interest was not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the issue. Whilst </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the application failed, the comments of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Foskett</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> J at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 213 are most pertinent and not to be ignored:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“Given the serious nature of the issues raised concerning young and vulnerable individuals, it would seem strange that a reputable ch</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">arity such as the Claimant should not be entitled to come to court and raise the kind of issues raised.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The standing proposals appear to be based on two areas of concern to the MOJ. Firstly that cases should not be brought by an interest group or charity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as they do not have a “direct and tangible interest” in the subject matter and use judicial review simply for publicity or delay reasons. Secondly, that the courts should not be dealing with matters and issues which are the “proper preserve of Parliament </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and the elected Government”.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The issue of sufficient interest should remain within the discretion of the courts to decide. The current test is more than adequate in preventing uninterested parties bringing cases without sufficient interest. The test was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ummarised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the case </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">R v Monopolies and Mergers Commission ex parte Argyll Group [1986] 1 WLR 763 773 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by Lord Donaldson, when he was Master of the Rolls: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“The first stage test which is applied on application for leave [permission] will lead to a ref</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">usal if the applicant has no interest whatsoever and is in truth no more than a meddlesome busybody. If, however, the application appears to be otherwise arguable and there is no other discretionary bar, such as dilatoriness on the part of the applicant, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">he applicant may expect to get leave to apply leaving the test of interest or standing to be reapplied as a matter of discretion on the hearing of the substantive application. At the second stage the strength of the applicant’s interest is one of the facto</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">rs to be weighed in the balance.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We refer the Committee to the comments made by Lord Reed in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Axa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> General Insurance Ltd v Lord Advocate [2011] UKSC 46</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (we acknowledge that this is a Scottish reported case but submit that the comments are of general applic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ation):</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">In some contexts, it is appropriate to require an applicant for judicial review to demonstrate that he has a particular interest in the matter complained of: the type of interest which is relevant, and therefore required in order to have standing,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> will depend upon the particular context. In other situations, such as where the excess or misuse of power affects the public generally, insistence upon a particular interest could prevent the matter being brought before court, and that in turn might disab</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">le the court from performing its function to protect the rule of law.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The judiciary robustly apply the current test. A more restrictive test could result in lack of access for the public. The issue of standing is a matter for the judiciary at the permiss</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ion stage </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We also support the right of any individual citizen to be able to bring a claim for judicial review regarding issues that are in the general public interest. The consultation refers to the case of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">R (on the application of Maya Evans) v </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Secretary of State for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Defence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> [2010] EWCH 1445 (Admin)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as seemingly being a reason to limit the definit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ion of standing. However we ask the Committee to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> take note of the comments of Lord Justice Richards at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2 where he recognizes that the Claimant, a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">peace activist opposed to the presence of UK and US forces in Afghanistan and had brought the proceedings in the public interest. He states: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“The claim itself is brought in the public interest with the benefit of public funding. It raises issues of real </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">substance concerning the risk to transferees, and, although the claimant’s standing to bring it was at one time in issue, the point has not been pursued by the Secretary of State.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We submit that it entirely appropriate that a concerned citizen should be able to challenge the legality of an executive decision. As Lord </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Diplock</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> stated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">in R v Inland Revenue Commissioners, ex parte National Federation of Self-employed and Small Businesse</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">s Ltd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“It would, in my view, be a grave lacuna in our system of public law if a pressure group … or even a single public-spirited taxpayer … were prevented </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">by outdated technical rules [of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">standing] from bringing the matter to the attention of the court t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">o vindicate the rule of law and get the unlawful conduct stopped.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are surprised that the MOJ has raised as an issue the fact that some judicial reviews maybe brought to seek publicity and promote political interests and hindering the process of proper</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> decision making by the executive. This seems to be irrelevant. Of course, Parliament and the elected government are there to make decisions on the public’s behalf but it cannot expect to do so without scrutiny. Judicial review brought on any terms, be it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">political or not, should be afforded the same regard by the court, as they currently are. The issue is not who brings the case, providing the sufficient interest test is met, but whether the government has acted unlawfully. Where it has there needs to be r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">edress.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NAYJ remains firmly of the view that the proposals in respect of standing are ill advised and maintain that this question should remain one for the courts. This is the only way to allow proper access to justice for all and to ensure the contin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ued application of the rule of law.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The MOJ has also raised the need to “reform” the position on interveners in judicial review proceedings. They specifically raise concerns that judicial review is being used by third party interveners as a “campaigning tool”. The NAYJ does not accept or und</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">erstand why the MOJ holds the idea of using judicial review as a “campaigning tool” a problem.  We do not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> agree that there is a ‘problem of judicial review being used as a campaigning tool’. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There may be occasions where judicial review is used in relation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to a campaigning agenda, but such intervention will only be allowed by the courts where there are grounds for considering that the executive has acted unlawfully. It is, in the view of the NAYJ, entirely appropriate that concerns of this nature should be r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eviewed by the courts.  J</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">udicial review is an important constitutional check on executive power and is perfectly legitimate form of challenging unla</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">wful </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by public bodies and ensuring human rights are protected.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is no merit whatsoever in li</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">miting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the ability of charities and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to intervene</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in judicial review proceedings. Such </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">input is invaluable to the process of judicial review. Charities and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> acting as interveners frequently provide expert evidence to the court and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> create a greater equality of arms between the individual seek</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing remedy and the government. We again refer the MOJ to the case of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">R on the application of HC (a child, by his litigation friend CC) v The Secretary of State for the Home Department and The Co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">mmissioner of the Police of the Metropolis [2013] EWCH 982 (Admin) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">discussed at paragraph 11 above.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Costs</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Paying for permission work in judicial review cases </span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the consultation paper the MOJ have suggested that providers should only be paid for work carried out on an application for judicial review in cases where permission is granted, or where the Legal Aid Agency (LAA) exercises its discretion to pay the pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vider in a case where proceedings are issued but the case concludes prior to a permission decision. The NAYJ objects in the strongest possible terms to the proposal that legal aid should only be paid in such circumstances.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The current test that the LAA ap</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ply to applications for legal aid for judicial review proceedings is a high one and is rigorously applied. To further restrict access to legal aid on the proposed terms would adversely affect the people’s right to hold the state to account</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and in so doing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">protect their human rights</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In the view of the NAYJ it might have a particularly adverse impact on children given that the issues involved are frequently more complex than in the case of adults and the outcome accordingly less predictable. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NAYJ remi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd the Committee </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that judicial review proceedings are distinct from any other kind of civil litigation. The issue of inequality of power is implicit given most proceedings involve an individual challenging the state and other public bodies. This power imba</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lance is particularly marked in the case of a child below the age of 18 years who require support in order to understand and ensure their rights.</span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are strict timetables and the individual is more often than not limited in terms of what evidence the de</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fendant will provide without an application for judicial review being lodged.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NAYJ is concerned that these proposals would either limit cases with proper merit being brought simply because of lack of funding, or, placing providers in choosing to take </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an unacceptable financial risk in running a case with no guarantee of costs being recovered. It is unacceptable that providers would have to bear the risk of bringing a claim to hold the state to account and we endorse </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and refer the Committee to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the commen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ts made by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Sir Stephen </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Sedley</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> in his article Beware Kite-Flyers, London Review of Books., </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Vol</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> 35 No. 17 12</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> September 2013 pgs 13-16</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘The superficially attractive reason is that it will inhibit the making of long-shot or speculative claims at public </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">expense, but it is supported by no evidence, and the argument advanced in support of it – that the claimant’s lawyer “is in the best position to know the strength of their client’s case” – displays a depressing degree of ignorance about how judicial review</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> works. More often than not, it is the defendant authority which holds most of the relevant cards, and in many cases it holds on to them for longer than it is supposed to, either because there is too little time for proper disclosure of documents or becaus</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">e sitting tight affords the best hope that the claim will go away. The departmental calculation is that indigent claimants’ lawyers will be deterred from taking on all but sure-fire claims. In proposing that other claimants can be left to their own devices</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> without injustice, the paper makes no attempt to confront the consequences: a plethora of claims made by litigants in person, clogging up the courts as judges try to discern arguable points in the chaos of paper, and costing public authorities large sums </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">in irrecoverable costs as they attempt to respond to such claims.’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There would therefore be a risk that many current providers would be reluctant or simply decide not to take on judicial review work. The NAYJ is particularly concerned as to how this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would affect children, given this area of work demands expertise and an extensive amount of work to be done prior to permission being granted.  A lot of firms would not be able to bear this financial risk. Limiting payment at the beginning of the case woul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d in effect reduce access to judicial review and therefore the individual’s ability to benefit from the rule of la</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">w. We ask the Committee </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to note the comments made by Lord Neuberger, the President of the UK Supreme Court, at the 2013 Tom </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sargant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Memorial L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ecture: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Cutting the cost of legal aid deprives the very people who most need the protection of the courts of the ability to get legal advice and representation. That is true whether one reduces the types of claim which qualify for legal aid or increases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> the stringency of the requirements of eligibility for legal aid. The recent changes have done both. If a person with a potential claim cannot get legal aid, there are two possible consequences. The first is that the claim is dropped: that is a rank denial</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> of justice and a blot on the rule of law. The second is that the claim is pursued, in which case it will be pursued inefficiently, and will take up much more of the court staffs’ time and of the judge’s time in and out of court. So that it means greater c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">osts for the court system, and delay for other litigants.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The MOJ has also failed to take into account the April 2013 reforms that introduced a fee for requests for an oral permission hearing and also the removal to an oral hearing where a claim is certified as being totally without merit by the paper permission </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">judge. The MOJ acknowledges in this consultation paper that these reforms will result in fewer oral permission hearings in the future and the NAYJ would ask the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Committee to request the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MOJ review</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the effect of these reforms before proc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eeding with any fur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ther ones.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would also ask the Committee to request</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that the MOJ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">acknowledge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the potential savings in Immigration and Asylum cases being removed from the Administrative Court to the U</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pper Tribunal and refer the Committee </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to the comments made by Lord N</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">euberger, again at the 2013 Tom </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sargant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Memorial Lecture: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">) The cause of the delays complained of is largely historic, thanks to the very recent removal of asylum and immigration cases from the Administrative Court to the Upper Tribunal, which the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">judges proposed in 2009. (ii) Cutting down time limits for JR applications may actually increase the work, due to rushed applications and many more requests for extensions of time. (iii) The cost-cutting proposals risk deterring a significant number of val</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">id applications, and will save a pathetically small sum.’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NAYJ endorses Lord Neuberger’s comments and would agree that these proposals are</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">likely to result in higher rather than lower costs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In this consultation paper the MOJ states that these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">proposals are designed to ‘encourage claimants and their legal representatives to consider more carefully the merits of bringing a judicial review and the way to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> handle proceedings’. We refer the Committee to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">strict merits and means test applied by the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> LAA and the equally robust approach taken by the courts in considering applications. Judicial review is most often than not the very last resort to an individual and the last remedy available when reasoned representations and submissions have been made to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the defendant without success. There seems to be a suggestion in this consultation paper that providers are exaggerating the merits of a judicial review claim in order to secure legal aid funding. Such a suggestion is completely unacceptable and shows a l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">evel of contempt on the MOJ’s behalf towards legal aid providers which the NAYJ finds seriously concerning.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NAYJ also w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ould ask the Committee to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">consider </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that the MOJ should conduct </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a proper review of the State and other defendant public bodies choos</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing to defend judicial review applications where there is no prospect of successfully doing so. This was raised by the government’s own lawyers in their response to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">“Transforming Legal Aid”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> consultation earlier this year. It has also been raised by Sir</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Stephen </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sedley</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Beware Kite-Flyers, London Review of Books </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Vol</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> 35 No 17 12</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> September 2013 pgs 13-16:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">More immediately, the consultation paper has nothing to say about public authorities which play the judicial review system at public expense... It</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> would be straightforward to propose that a public body which unjustifiably resists the grant of permission in a viable case should pay the costs of doing so; but the consultation paper has nothing to say about this, or about penalising late disclosure, or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> about other ways of saving public funds.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Arguably some of the successful reviews involving young people in the criminal justice system cited above were cases where the government’s opposition to the application was of this form. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As we have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> stated throughout this paper</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, judicial review is the only means by which the individual can hold the state to account. The proposal that an individual’s ability to do this will be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dependent on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">their ability to pay or for a provider to take a financial ris</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">k is a further attack on the individual’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">human </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rights, access to justice and the rule of law.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="49" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are also concerned regarding the decision of payment lying in the hands of the LAA or with any </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">payment scheme which is uncertain. In addition, the system suggested would be unwieldy, cumbersome and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">result </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in even more</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> non-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">chargeable work for providers as it would need a full review of the case in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">order to submit a claim to be assessed on “particular</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> facts”.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This would not take into account the costs that have arisen as a result of the conduct of the defendant.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="50" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> success of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> proposal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would be dep</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">endent</span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on the LAA staff acting as e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ffective costs judges. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This would result in time and cost </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">implications in terms of the necessary training required.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="51" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We ask the Committee to consider that t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hese proposals in respect of legal aid provision </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">premature and misguided in their intention t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o save costs. The cost of implemen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tation is likely to exceed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the cost of the current system which the NAYJ believes should be maintained.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In any event, the NAYJ believes that where the issue of safeguarding the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> human</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> rights of vulnerable young people is at stake, fiscal savings should be considered only where it can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be demonstrated that they would not undermine such safeguards. In the view of the NAYJ, the government has failed to do so. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="52" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In respect of whether the courts should consider awarding the costs of an oral permission hearing as a </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">       matter of course </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rather than just in exceptional circumstances, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he NAYJ be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lieves this is a matter for the     </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">       </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">court to decide on each individual case. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Wasted Costs Orders  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="53" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We do not accept that there is a need for reform of the current system of Wasted Cost </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Orders (WCOs) and this consultation paper fails to disclose any evidence to justify why this is the case. The fact that WCOs are rarely made does not mean they should be made more.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="54" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The current conduct of a legal representative for which a WCO can be made</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> against is widely defined by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">s51(7) of the Senior Courts Act 1981</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as any “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">improper, unreasonable or negligent act or omission’. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NAYJ does not believe that this definition needs extending in any way.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="55" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Any suggestion that a WCO could be made where a wea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">k case </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has been pursued</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is completely opposed by the NAYJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The issue of holding a lawyer to account for pursuing a weak case is one that the courts have considered and given clear judgment on, stating that there are important public police reasons why this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> should not happen. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the case of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Ridehalgh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> v </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Horsefield</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> [1994] Ch 205 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sir Thomas Bingham, when he was Master of the Rolls, stated: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“Legal representatives will, of course, whether barristers or solicitors, advice clients of the perceived weakness of their case and of the risk of failure. But clients are free to reject advice and insist that cases be litigated. It is rarely if ever safe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> for a court to assume that a hopeless case is being litigated on the advice of the lawyers involved. They are there to present the case; it is (as Samuel Johnson unforgettably pointed out) for the judge and not the lawyers to judge it.” </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Given that, as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">noted previously, the legal issues involved in representing children are </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">frequently more complex any increased threat of WCO might result in young people in trouble with the law finding it increasingly difficult to secure representation for judicial </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">review.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Protective costs orders </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Question 26: What is your view on whether it is appropriate to stipulate that PCOs will not be available in any case where there is an individual or private interest regardless of whether there is a wider public interest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">?  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="56" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NAYJ is satisfied with the current scheme in place for Protective Costs Orders (PCOs)and have grav</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e concerns regarding the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">proposal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that PCOs should not be available in any case where there is an individual or private interest regardless of whether there is a wider public interest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Any changes in these terms would deter legitimate claims in the public interest being pursued thus restr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">icting the public’s access to justice to hold the state to account. We are of the view that this would particularly have an adverse effect on children. Many judicial review cases involving children are brought on public interest grounds.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="57" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PCOs enable claim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ants in cases brough</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t in the public interest reassurance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that they will not face substantial costs against them, and we are not aware of any abuse of the provisions. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Research conducted by the Public Law Project and the University of Essex, funded by the Nu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ffield Foundation, reveals that during the 20 month period between July 2010 and February 2012 there were only seven cases decided by the Administrative Court at final hearing in which a PCO had been granted, and these were awarded to well respected NGOs s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uch as Medical Justice and the Child Poverty Action Group.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Costs arising from the involvement of third party interveners and non-parties </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="58" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> principle </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">we can accept </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that interveners should bear their own costs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but remain satisfied that this can also remain at the discretion of the courts. We are unaware that this is something that is an issue and the MOJ has provided no evidence in this consultation paper to suggest that it is. This is an issue that could have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an adverse effect on children, who are often dependant on third party interveners becoming involved in their cases.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Impact Assessment and Equalities Impacts </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="59" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Impact Assessment (IA) </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MoJ</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 215 states that the L</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">AA will</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have the discretion to pay for work undertaken in certain cases which conclude prior to a permission decision.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> However, this is “front-loaded” to the disadvantage of the provider given the LAA would not be exercising this discretion until essential and ne</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cessary work has already been undertaken and costs inc</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">urred as a result of it. The Committee is asked to consider </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">there would also be a further layer of costs to providers should the LAA’s discretion not be properly applied resulting in the need for an app</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eal.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="60" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As the extent to which the discretion of the LAA will extend in such claims, many providers may feel this is a financial risk too far and simply cease to do judicial rev</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">iew work. This would adversely a</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ffect those specialist Public Law solicitors and </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">chambers. It would al</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">so a</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ffect those firms that are also likely to struggle as a result of the other legal aid proposals currently under consultation. In turn this will simply disadvantage those individuals seeking redress from the state and public </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">authorities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="61" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NAYJ does not agree with the suggestion in </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Impact Assessment (IA) </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MoJ</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 215 that firms may be able to continue with this line of work but with funding from alternative sources</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Third party groups such as charities and law centres are alread</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y facing substantial reductions in respect of their funding. The proposals as a whole in this consultation paper also makes judicial review work even more demanding and risky than it already is.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="62" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Impact Assessment</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 210, 212, and 215 </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">suggests that “</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in c</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ases where less work is undertaken resources would be freed for other profitable act</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ivities” is completely unacceptable and demonstrates that complete lack of understanding the MOJ have about legal firms that practise public law</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The specialist lawyers, if</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not able to practice in this area, would not necessary become insolvency lawyers. We would welcome the </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Committee requesting the </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MOJ to define what other “profitable activities” </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">they would suggest public law lawyers undertake. The MOJ need to accept that i</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f funding ceases to be available for judicial review work, many cases with merit will cease to be brought and irrational and unlawful behaviour by the state and public authorities will not be</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> challenged. Once again, the Committee is asked to accept </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the det</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rimental effect this would have on the rule of law.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Procedural</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> as opposed to substantive defects in decisions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> </span></p><ol start="63" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the consultation the MOJ suggests a case for the consideration of the "no difference” argument being brought forward to the permission stage on the assertion of the defendant in the Acknowledgment of Service. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NAYJ is opposed to the “no difference ar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gument” being heard at the permission stage and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would ask the Committee to also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">question with concern the reasoning behind this proposal.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="64" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The need for government and public bodies to have a proper system of lawful procedure in place is absolutely essentia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l. Yet these proposals suggest that where the correct decision making procedures have not been followed, but the same decision would have been reached if they had been, is not something that demands scrutiny or concern. The danger of such a proposal is tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t it would remove any incentive for public bodies to follow lawful procedure. If correct procedures are followed then well reasoned decisions should follow.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="65" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are particularly concerned at the impact this proposal could have on children, giv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">en our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">comments in paragraphs 26 – 27</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">above that children are on the receiving end of decisions from public authorities more than adults are. This could have an inflated negative effect on children.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="66" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Procedural impropriety cases can often have a significant effec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t on unlawful policies that would otherwise be put into effect. For example in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">R (on the application of C) v Secretary Of State For Justice [2008] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Civ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> 882</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the court quashed new Secure Training Centre (Amendment) Rules 2007, which substantially widened</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the purposes for which force or “restraint” could be used against children </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">held in Secure Training </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, an issue pertinent to children’s Article 5 rights.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> While this had previously been limited to very specific circumstances, e.g. to prevent escape, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he new rules allowed force to be used for the purpose of “ensuring good order and discipline.” The lack of proper consultation and impact assessment led to the quashing of these regulations which would have had an important impact on the safety and lives o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f children living in these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">centres</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The importance of this decision is clear and yet under these proposals the MOJ would have regarded the application as one brought on mere technicalities and it may well have not proceeded, to the detriment of children an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d the public at large.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="67" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We also ask the Committee to accept that the MOJ has, in any event, put forward no evidence to  suggest that the current system is flawed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="68" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NAYJ also asks the Committee to accept our concern that there is a risk that defendants </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are likely to consider it to their advantage to assert the “no difference” argument in their Acknowledgement of Service to try to avoid a full hearing. This will result in an increase in the need for oral hearings, extra preparation and lengthier pleadings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Therefore this particular proposal could in fact result in higher rather than lower costs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="69" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is no evidence to suggest judicial reviews brought on grounds of procedural defects are cause for concern. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The MOJ should rather direct its concerns at publ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ic authorities not following proper and lawful procedure rather than at restricting the public’s ability to challenge those unlawful decisions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The Public Sector Equality Duty and Judicial Review </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="70" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Under the Equality Act 2010 the Public Sector Equality D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uty (PSED) requires all public bodies to ensure that they eliminate discrimination in the exercise of their functions, advance equality of opportunities and foster good relations between people when carrying out their activities. The NAYJ are of the view t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hat the PSED is essential to protect and advance the rights of all to ensure equality of arms. The consultation suggests that judicial review is not the most efficient way to address those public bodies that fail to comply with this duty as the outcome is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">simply for that public body being asked to reconsider their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and correct it.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="71" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NAYJ does not accept that the volume of such judicial review applications raises any concern. This is particularly true in the case of children in trouble with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">law.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="72" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If the MOJ is considering introducing a different system, such as a tribunal system, to deal with PSED cases than it should ensure that legal aid is still available for claimants and that the tribunal has the same powers as the High Court in terms of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> making quashing, mandatory and prohibiting orders.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="73" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although the MOJ appears to be concerned of the volume and nature of PSED-related judicial reviews, they have not put forward any evidence to support this. We would ask the Committee to request such evid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ence from the MOJ if it wishes to maintain this concern. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NAYJ is not aware that the volume and nature of PSED-related judicial review challenges is an issue. We are of the view that it is essential that public bodies are held to account in respect of t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hese duties and remain of the view judicial review is the most appropriate way to do so.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Such applications are essential to uphold Article 14 rights regarding protection from discrimination.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">In Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="74" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We ask the Committee to accept and share our co</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#222222; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ncerns that the effect of these proposals on groups of vulnerable individuals, who are more likely to have a protected characteristic, will be devastating.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="75" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are particularly concerned at the negative impact this will have on children. We have cited judi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cial review cases that have ensured that our children’s rights are protected at times of need such as in the criminal justice syste</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">m or the secure estate. The proposals show</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> no regard for dealing with children as a separate grou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">p of people with separate ne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eds and we ask the Committee to robustly challenge this. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> If these proposals are to be implemented in any part then we would maintain that any changes should not apply to children.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">18 November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>